<h2 id="6550">22. Matching ePIDs</h2>
<div class="sectionbody">
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Since 15 August 2018, it is mandatory to match products from specific categories which you want to offer on eBay with ePIDs. An ePID (eBay Product ID) is an eBay-specific product identification that is provided by eBay. ePIDs are used to display identical products in a cluster on eBay. When buyers click on the product, they can choose an offer.<br></p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>A product which is sold on eBay as a single product and in a set can have multiple ePIDs.</p>
</div>
<div class="admonitionblock tip">
<table>
<tbody><tr>
<td class="icon">
<i class="fa icon-tip" title="Tip"></i>
</td>
<td class="content">
<div class="title">Automatic ePID matching</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>New listings are automatically matched with an ePID when they are started. If there is more than one ePID available for a listing, then the first ePID is automatically matched. Further ePIDs are saved in a log message.<br>
For existing listings, you have to match ePIDs manually.</p>
</div>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Link variations with ePIDs in the <strong>Setup » Markets » eBay » ePID matching</strong> menu.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Requirements for matching variations with ePIDs:</p>
</div>
<div class="ulist">
<ul>
<li>
<p>The variation that you want to match with an ePID has to have an active or hidden listing.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>The selection <strong>Transmit ePID</strong> must be selected for the <strong>Transfer as item number</strong> option within the <strong>Listings » Edit listings » [Open listing ID] » Edit listing</strong> menu.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>An EAN must be saved for the variation within <strong>Item » Edit item » [Open item] » Tab: Variation ID</strong> in the <strong>Barcode</strong> area.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>- In the <strong>Setup » Markets » eBay » Settings » Tab: Initial settings</strong> menu, the <strong>Add item details from the eBay catalogue</strong> option has to be set to <strong>Yes</strong>.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>At the moment, ePID matching is only possible for the platforms eBay Germany, eBay UK, eBay United States, eBay Canada, and eBay Australia.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>At the moment, only products from specific eBay categories can be matched with ePIDs. Further information about the affected categories is available <a href="https://developer.ebay.com/api-docs/sell/static/inventory/pbse-phase1-categories.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">here</a>&nbsp;<span class="icon "><i class="fa fa-external-link  "></i></span>.</p>
</li>
</ul>
</div>
<div class="admonitionblock important">
<table>
<tbody><tr>
<td class="icon">
<i class="fa icon-important" title="Important"></i>
</td>
<td class="content">
<div class="title">OAuth2 authentication required</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>In order to link ePIDs, you have to authenticate your eBay account for OAuth2 in the <strong>Setup » Markets » eBay » Accounts » OAuth2</strong> menu.</p>
</div>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
<div class="paragraph instruction">
<p>Matching ePIDs:</p>
</div>
<div class="olist arabic">
<ol class="arabic">
<li>
<p>Go to <strong>Setup » Markets » eBay » ePID matching</strong>.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Click on <strong>Search</strong> (<span class="icon blue"><i class="fa fa-search  "></i></span>).<br>
→ All variations without an ePID from the last day are displayed in the overview.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Click on the variation that you want to match with an ePID.<br>
→ All available ePIDs for this variation are displayed.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Cick on <strong>Match ePID</strong> in the field of the ePID that you want to match.</p>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
